<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="lesson5_4" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title> Quantum State Representation: Vectors</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>While bra-ket notation is handy and concise, it has its limitations when it comes to being
      able
      to handle every possible complex state and gate sequence.</p>
  </introduction>

  <subsection xml:id="vector_state" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Vector Quantum Representation</title>

    <p> The purpose of vector notation is to allow us to calculate the output of quantum gates in
      all situations. Vector notation loses some of the explicit information in bra-ket notation <mdash />
      namely, the information about what each probability amplitude is tied to. Instead, we have to
      remember the proper order. </p>

    <sidebyside widths="55% 5% 40%" valign="top">
      <p> Bra-ket notation is always sorted by the value in the ket (i.e. the outcome) <mdash /> the
        sorting order is, from left to right, smallest to largest. Vector notation uses the same
        order<mdash />smallest to largest<mdash />but it is depicted from top to bottom.</p>
      <p> </p>
      <image source="L5.3.brakettovector.png" />
    </sidebyside>

    <p> Here are some examples: </p>

    <p>
      <image source="L5.3.brakettovectorexamples.png" width="70%" />
    </p>

    <p> You have to be careful, though, to express bra-ket notation in the proper order.
      If the bra-ket order is incorrect, then you might accidentally put the terms in the
      wrong locations in the vector. This is the correct conversion for out-of-order bra-ket states: </p>

    <p>
      <image source="L5.3.wrongorder.png" width="30%" />
    </p>

    <exercise label="Vector-Notation-Exercise-1">
      <title>Vector Notation Exercise 1</title>
      <idx>vector notation exercise 1</idx>
      <statement>
        <p>What is the correct vector notation for the state <m>\frac{\sqrt{15}}{4} \ket{1} + \frac{1}{4} \ket{0}</m>?</p>
      </statement>
      <choices randomize="yes">
        <choice correct="yes">
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\begin{bmatrix}\frac{1}{4}\\\frac{\sqrt{15}}{4}\end{bmatrix}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\begin{bmatrix}0\\1\end{bmatrix}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\begin{bmatrix}\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\\\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\end{bmatrix}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p>Cannot be represented</p>
          </statement>
        </choice>
      </choices>
    </exercise>

    <exercise label="Vector-Notation-Exercise-2">
      <title>Vector Notation Exercise 2</title>
      <idx>vector notation exercise 2</idx>
      <statement>
        <p>What is the correct bra-ket notation for the following state:</p>
        <md>  \begin{bmatrix}\frac{1}{\sqrt{6}}\\\frac{1}{\sqrt{3}}\\\frac{1}{\sqrt{3}}\\\frac{1}{\sqrt{6}}\end{bmatrix} </md>
      </statement>
      <choices randomize="yes">
        <choice correct="yes">
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\frac{1}{\sqrt{6}} \ket{00} + \frac{1}{\sqrt{3}} \ket{01} + \frac{1}{\sqrt{3}} \ket{10} + \frac{1}{\sqrt{6}} \ket{11} </m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\frac{1}{\sqrt{6}} \ket{0} + \frac{1}{\sqrt{3}} \ket{1}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\frac{1}{\sqrt{6}} \ket{00} + \frac{1}{\sqrt{6}} \ket{01} + \frac{1}{\sqrt{3}} \ket{10} + \frac{1}{\sqrt{3}} \ket{11} </m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\frac{1}{2} \ket{00} + \frac{1}{2} \ket{01} + \frac{1}{2} \ket{10} + \frac{1}{2} \ket{11} </m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </choice>
      </choices>
      <hint>
        <p>
          Remember to map the probability amplitudes in the correct order from the vector notation.
        </p>
      </hint>
    </exercise>

    <exercise label="Vector-Notation-Exercise-3">
      <title>Vector Notation Exercise 3</title>
      <idx>vector notation exercise 3</idx>
      <introduction>
        <p>Consider the following quantum state:</p>
        <md>  \begin{bmatrix}\frac{2}{\sqrt{5}}\\\frac{1}{\sqrt{5}}\end{bmatrix} </md>
      </introduction>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>What is the probability of measuring 0?</p>
        </statement>
        <choices randomize="yes">
          <choice>
            <statement>
              <p>
                <m>\frac{2}{\sqrt{5}}</m>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </choice>
          <choice>
            <statement>
              <p><m>\frac{1}{5}</m> or 20%</p>
            </statement>
          </choice>
          <choice>
            <statement>
              <p><m>\frac{2}{5}</m> or 40%</p>
            </statement>
          </choice>
          <choice correct="yes">
            <statement>
              <p><m>\frac{4}{5}</m> or 80%</p>
            </statement>
          </choice>
        </choices>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>What is the probability of measuring a 1?</p>
        </statement>
        <choices randomize="yes">
          <choice>
            <statement>
              <p>
                <m>\frac{1}{\sqrt{5}}</m>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </choice>
          <choice correct="yes">
            <statement>
              <p><m>\frac{1}{5}</m> or 20%</p>
            </statement>
          </choice>
          <choice>
            <statement>
              <p><m>\frac{2}{5}</m> or 40%</p>
            </statement>
          </choice>
          <choice>
            <statement>
              <p><m>\frac{4}{5}</m> or 80%</p>
            </statement>
          </choice>
        </choices>
      </task>
    </exercise>

    <exercise label="Vector-Notation-Exercise-4">
      <!-- 228 Gradescope HW2 6.2 -->
      <title>Vector Notation Exercise 4</title>
      <idx>vector notation exercise 4</idx>
      <statement>
        <p>Consider the following quantum state:</p>
        <p>
          <image source="L4_3_2_E.png" width="20%" />
        </p>
        <p>What is the proper way to express this state in vector notation?</p>
      </statement>
      <choices randomize="yes">
        <choice correct="yes">
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\begin{bmatrix}\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\\ - \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\end{bmatrix}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\begin{bmatrix}- \frac{1}{2} \\ \frac{1}{2}\end{bmatrix}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\begin{bmatrix}0\\1\end{bmatrix}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\ket{0} + \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \ket{1}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\begin{bmatrix} \frac{1}{2} \\ -\frac{1}{2}\end{bmatrix}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </choice>
      </choices>
    </exercise>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="sec_vector_multi_qubit" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Multi-Qubit Vector Notation</title>

    <p> Vector notation is highly flexible, so that when you are representing multiple qubits, you
      just need enough spots to keep track of all possible combinations of the qubit values. For
      example, for two-qubit systems, you would have a vector with 4 elements, corresponding to <m>00</m>
      , <m>01</m>, <m>10</m>, and <m>11</m>. So, a state of the form <m>a\ket{00} + b\ket{01} + c\ket{10} + d\ket{11}</m> would be transformed to: </p>
    <md>
      <mrow> \begin{bmatrix}a\\b\\c\\d\end{bmatrix} </mrow>
    </md>

    <p> Combining two qubit states into a single two-qubit state involves a new operation on
      vectors. This is called a <term>tensor product</term>. The effect of the operation is
      identical to how we combine states in bra-ket notation, but let's walk through how a tensor
      product works in the vector world. Let's say we want to combine the two states <m>\ket{\psi_1} = \begin{bmatrix}a\\b\end{bmatrix}</m> and <m>\ket{\psi_2} = \begin{bmatrix}c\\d\end{bmatrix}</m>.
      In order to do so, we perform the tensor product <m>\ket{\psi_1} \otimes \ket{\psi_2}</m>.</p>

    <p> Here is how I like to think of performing a tensor product <m>A \otimes B</m>. The idea is to "stuff" a
      copy of the second operand (<m>B</m>) inside each element of <m>A</m>. Then, you multiply each
      term of <m>B</m> with the element of <m>A</m> that it overlaps, and you get your result! </p>

    <p>
      <image source="2_Qubit_Tensor_Product.gif" width="50%" />
    </p>

    <md>
      <mrow> \begin{bmatrix}a\\b\end{bmatrix} \otimes \begin{bmatrix}c\\d\end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix}ac\\ad\\bc\\bd\end{bmatrix} </mrow>
    </md>

    <p>We can see that this is equivalent to the calculation using bra-ket notation:</p>
    <md>
      <mrow> (a\ket{0} + b\ket{1}) \otimes (c\ket{0} + d\ket{1}) = ac\ket{00} + ad\ket{01} + bc\ket{10} + bd\ket{11} </mrow>
    </md>

    <exercise label="Vector-Notation-Multi-Qubit-Exercise-1">
      <title>Vector Notation Multi-Qubit Exercise 1</title>
      <idx>vector notation multi-qubit exercise 1</idx>
      <statement>
        <p>Convert the following 2-qubit bra-ket notation into vector notation:</p>
        <md>  \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \ket{00} + 0 \ket{01} + \frac{1}{2} \ket{10} + 0 \ket{11} </md>
      </statement>
      <choices randomize="yes">
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\begin{bmatrix}\frac{3}{4}\\0\\\frac{1}{4}\\0\end{bmatrix}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </choice>
        <choice correct="yes">
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\begin{bmatrix}\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}\\0\\\frac{1}{2}\\0\end{bmatrix}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\begin{bmatrix}\frac{1}{2}\\0\\\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}\\0\end{bmatrix}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\begin{bmatrix}0\\\frac{1}{2}\\0\\\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}\end{bmatrix}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </choice>
      </choices>
    </exercise>

    <exercise label="Vector-Notation-Multi-Qubit-Exercise-2">
      <title>Vector Notation Multi-Qubit Exercise 2</title>
      <idx>vector notation multi-qubit exercise 2</idx>
      <statement>
        <p>Convert the following 2-qubit vector notation into bra-ket notation:</p>
        <md>  \begin{bmatrix}\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\\0\\\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\\0\end{bmatrix} </md>
      </statement>
      <choices randomize="yes">
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \ket{01} + \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \ket{11}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\frac{1}{2} \ket{01} + \frac{1}{2} \ket{11}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\frac{1}{2} \ket{00} + \frac{1}{2} \ket{10}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </choice>
        <choice correct="yes">
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \ket{00} + \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \ket{10}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </choice>
      </choices>
    </exercise>

    <exercise label="Vector-Notation-Multi-Qubit-Exercise-3">
      <title>Vector Notation Multi-Qubit Exercise 3</title>
      <idx>vector notation multi-qubit exercise 3</idx>
      <statement>
        <p>Combine the following single-qubit states into a 2-qubit vector:</p>
        <md>  \begin{bmatrix}\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\\\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\end{bmatrix} \otimes \begin{bmatrix}0\\-1\end{bmatrix} </md>
      </statement>
      <choices randomize="yes">
        <choice correct="yes">
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\begin{bmatrix}0\\-\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\\0\\-\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\end{bmatrix}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\begin{bmatrix}0\\0\\-\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\\-\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\end{bmatrix}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\begin{bmatrix}\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\\\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\\-\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\\-\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\end{bmatrix}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\begin{bmatrix}\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\\\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\\0\\-1\end{bmatrix}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </choice>
      </choices>
      <hint>
        <p>
          To perform a tensor product, "stuff" copies of the second state into each element in the
          first state.
        </p>
      </hint>
    </exercise>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="vector_state_simplification" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Vector State Simplification</title>

    <p> Generally, the state simplification rules are the same for vectors and for bra-ket notation,
      with one major exception: you can <em>never remove a state</em>! You must retain the 0 in the
      vector. </p>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>The order of the outcomes is <em>always</em> in increasing numeric order (starting with
          all 0's and ending with all 1's). This is even more important for vector notation because
          we don't explicitly write the outcome for each entry in the vector. </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>You may <em>not</em> omit any term whose probability is 0. <!-- (make images of these
          two,
        both bra-ket and vector: |0> and pair it with the
      state: 50/50 00 vs 11) -->
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>The state with all 0's (the topmost entry in the vector) is never in negative phase. Once
          again, if the topmost entry is negative, you can multiply the whole vector by <m>-1</m> and
          get an equivalent state. </p>
      </li>
    </ol>

    <p>Just like in bra-ket notation, the sum of the squares of each entry in the vector (which is
      the <em>probability amplitude</em>) should add up to 1, to ensure the probabilities are valid.</p>

    <p>If all outcomes are the same probability, you can choose to factor out a common factor and
      put that in front of the vector for simplicity's sake. </p>
    <p>
      <image source="L5.3.pullfactor.png" width="70%" />
    </p>

    <exercise label="Vector-Notation-Simplification">
      <title>Vector Notation Simplification</title>
      <idx>vector notation simplification</idx>
      <statement>
        <p> Choose all vector representations of the state <m>\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \ket{10} + \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \ket{01}</m>.</p>
      </statement>
      <choices randomize="yes">
        <choice correct="yes">
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m> \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \begin{bmatrix}0\\1\\1\\0\end{bmatrix} </m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </choice>
        <choice correct="yes">
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m> \begin{bmatrix}0\\\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\\\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\\0\end{bmatrix} </m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m> \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \begin{bmatrix}1\\0\end{bmatrix} + \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \begin{bmatrix}0\\1\end{bmatrix}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m> \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \begin{bmatrix}1\\1\\1\\1\end{bmatrix} </m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </choice>
      </choices>
    </exercise>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="quantum_gate_representation" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Quantum Gate Representation</title>

    <p> In vector notation, quantum gates are represented as a <term>matrix</term>, which is a grid
      of numbers. Quantum gates are always squares<mdash />that is, the length is always equal the
      width. They are also of pre-determined size. A gate that operates on <m>n</m> bits has length
      and width <m>2^n</m>. That means a 1-qubit gate is a <m>2\times 2</m> matrix, 2-qubit gate is a <m>4\times 4</m>
      matrix, and a 3-qubit gate is an <m>8\times 8</m> matrix. </p>

    <p> Here are a few gates and their representations. But we can't do anything useful with
      them until we learn to calculate with them!!</p>

    <p>
      <image source="L5.4.nothmatrices.png" width="50%" />
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="matrix_multiplication" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Matrix Multiplication to Apply Gates</title>
    <p> To calculate the result of a gate acting on a state, we perform <term>matrix multiplication</term>
      where the matrix representing the gate is multiplied with the vector form of the state. Here
      is how to perform matrix multiplication:</p>

    <p>
      <image source="L5.4.matrixmultiply.gif" width="90%" />
    </p>

    <p> Let's see if we can calculate this on a gate for which we know the output. We know that if
      we start with the state <m>\ket{0}</m>, a <c>NOT</c> gate results in the state <m>\ket{1}</m>, and vice versa.
      So let's use that example to practice matrix multiplication. </p>

    <p>
      <image source="L5.4.NOT0.png" width="50%" />
    </p>

    <p>In order to perform this operation, we multiply the gate's matrix form with the vector state.</p>

    <md>
      <mrow> \begin{bmatrix}0\amp1\\1\amp0\end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix}1\\0\end{bmatrix} </mrow>
    </md>

    <p>Now, we follow the rules above of matrix multiplication:</p>

    <md>
      <mrow>
        \begin{bmatrix}0\amp1\\1\amp0\end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix}1\\0\end{bmatrix}
        \amp= \begin{bmatrix}(0 \times 1) + (1 \times 0) \\ (1 \times 1) + (0 \times 0)\end{bmatrix}
      </mrow>
      <mrow>
        \amp= \begin{bmatrix}0\\1\end{bmatrix}
      </mrow>
    </md>

    <p>Voilà! Applying a <c>NOT</c> gate on the <m>\ket{0}</m> state leads to <m>\ket{1}</m>!</p>

    <exercise label="Applying-Gate-H">
      <title>Applying a Gate in Vector Notation: <c>H</c></title>
      <idx>applying a gate in vector notation h</idx>
      <introduction>
        <p> In this exercise we will work through applying the <c>H</c> gate on the <m>\ket{1}</m> state.
          Below is the matrix representation for the <c>H</c> gate: </p>
        <md>\begin{bmatrix}\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \amp \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \\ \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \amp -\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\end{bmatrix}</md>
      </introduction>
      <task>
        <title><m>\ket{1}</m> in vector notation</title>
        <statement>
          <p>Let's start by expressing our starting state in vector notation. What is the vector
            notation for <m>\ket{1}</m>? </p>
        </statement>
        <choices randomize="yes">
          <choice correct="yes">
            <statement>
              <p>
                <m>\begin{bmatrix}0\\1\end{bmatrix}</m>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </choice>
          <choice>
            <statement>
              <p>
                <m>\begin{bmatrix}1\\0\end{bmatrix}</m>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </choice>
          <choice>
            <statement>
              <p>
                <m>\begin{bmatrix}1\\1\end{bmatrix}</m>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </choice>
          <choice>
            <statement>
              <p>
                <m>\begin{bmatrix}\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\\\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\end{bmatrix}</m>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </choice>
        </choices>
      </task>
      <task>
        <title>Order of multiplication</title>
        <statement>
          <p> Now that we have our matrix representation for the <c>H</c> gate and the vector
            representation for our starting state <m>\ket{1}</m>, the next step is to set up the
            multiplication. What is the correct order to compute the resulting state from applying
            the gate on the state? </p>
        </statement>
        <choices randomize="yes">
          <choice correct="yes">
            <statement>
              <p>
                <m>\begin{bmatrix}\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \amp \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \\ \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \amp -\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\end{bmatrix}
            \begin{bmatrix}0\\1\end{bmatrix}</m>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </choice>
          <choice>
            <statement>
              <p>
                <m>
            \begin{bmatrix}0\\1\end{bmatrix}
          \begin{bmatrix}\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \amp \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \\ \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \amp -\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\end{bmatrix}</m>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </choice>
          <choice>
            <statement>
              <p>The order does not matter</p>
            </statement>
          </choice>
        </choices>
      </task>
      <task>
        <introduction>
          <p>
            Now, let's perform the matrix multiplication. We need to compute the two entries in our
            resulting vector.
          </p>
        </introduction>
        <task>
          <title>Upper entry of resulting vector</title>
          <statement>
            <p> What is the value of the <em>upper</em> entry in the resulting vector? </p>
          </statement>
          <choices randomize="yes">
            <choice correct="yes">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  <m>\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \times 0 + \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \times 1 = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}</m>
                </p>
              </statement>
            </choice>
            <choice>
              <statement>
                <p>
                  <m>\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \times 1 + - \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \times 1 = 0</m>
                </p>
              </statement>
            </choice>
            <choice>
              <statement>
                <p>
                  <m>\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \times 0 + - \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \times 1 = - \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}</m>
                </p>
              </statement>
            </choice>
            <choice>
              <statement>
                <p>
                  <m>\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \times 0 + \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \times 0 = 0</m>
                </p>
              </statement>
            </choice>
          </choices>
        </task>
        <task>
          <title>Lower entry of resulting vector</title>
          <statement>
            <p> What is the value of the <em>lower</em> entry in the resulting vector? </p>
          </statement>
          <choices randomize="yes">
            <choice correct="yes">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  <m>\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \times 0 + - \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \times 1 = - \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}</m>
                </p>
              </statement>
            </choice>
            <choice>
              <statement>
                <p>
                  <m>\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \times 1 + - \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \times 1 = 0</m>
                </p>
              </statement>
            </choice>
            <choice>
              <statement>
                <p>
                  <m>\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \times 0 + \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \times 1 = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}</m>
                </p>
              </statement>
            </choice>
            <choice>
              <statement>
                <p>
                  <m>\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \times 0 + \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \times 0 = 0</m>
                </p>
              </statement>
            </choice>
          </choices>
        </task>
      </task>
      <conclusion>
        <p>Thus, we see that the result of our matrix multiplication is:</p>
        <md>
          \begin{bmatrix}\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \amp \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \\ \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \amp -\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\end{bmatrix}
            \begin{bmatrix}0\\1\end{bmatrix} =
            \begin{bmatrix}\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\\- \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\end{bmatrix}
        </md>
        <p>We confirmed that applying the <c>H</c> gate to the <m>\ket{1}</m> state gives us <m>\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \ket{0} - \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \ket{1}</m>!</p>
      </conclusion>
    </exercise>

    <p>Now that we have some practice working with matrix multiplication, let's try to derive the
      matrix representation of the <c>Z</c> gate.</p>

    <example xml:id="example-derive-z-matrix">
      <title>Deriving the Matrix Representation of <c>Z</c></title>
      <p> Our overall approach to derive the matrix representation of the <c>Z</c> gate is going to
        be based on what we already know about its behavior. As we have seen before, the following
        is the behavior of <c>Z</c> on our basis states: </p>
      <md>
        <mrow>Z \ket{0} \amp = \ket{0}</mrow>
        <mrow>Z \ket{1} \amp = -\ket{1}</mrow>
      </md>

      <p>How can we derive the matrix representation of <c>Z</c> here? Let's start by just looking at
        the first equation above, knowing that <m>\ket{0} = \begin{bmatrix}1\\0\end{bmatrix}</m>, and filling in what we know.</p>

      <md>Z \begin{bmatrix}1\\0\end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix}1\\0\end{bmatrix}</md>

      <p>Now, since the <c>Z</c> gate is a 1-qubit gate, we know that it must be 2 rows and 2 columns
        (i.e. a <m>2 \times 2</m> matrix). Our goal is to fill it out, like so:</p>

      <md>Z = \begin{bmatrix}a \amp b \\ c \amp d\end{bmatrix}</md>

      <p>Now we can plug this into our first equation:</p>

      <md>\begin{bmatrix}a \amp b \\ c \amp d\end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}1\\0\end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix}1\\0\end{bmatrix}</md>

      <p>Let's perform matrix multiplication on the left hand side of this equation:</p>

      <md>
        <mrow>\begin{bmatrix}a \times 1 + b \times 0 \\ c \times 1 + d \times 0\end{bmatrix} \amp = \begin{bmatrix}1\\0\end{bmatrix}</mrow>
        <mrow>\Rightarrow \begin{bmatrix}a\\ c\end{bmatrix} \amp = \begin{bmatrix}1\\0\end{bmatrix}</mrow>
      </md>

      <p>Now we can just compare entries in the vectors on either side of the equation!</p>

      <md>
        \Rightarrow a = 1, c = 0
      </md>

      <p>Okay, we now know two of the four numbers in the <c>Z</c> gate! Let's repeat the same
        process by walking through its action on the <m>\ket{1}</m> state: </p>

      <md>
        <mrow>Z \ket{1} \amp = -\ket{1}</mrow>
        <mrow>\Rightarrow \begin{bmatrix}a \amp b \\ c \amp d\end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}0\\1\end{bmatrix} \amp = \begin{bmatrix}0\\-1\end{bmatrix}</mrow>
        <mrow>\Rightarrow \begin{bmatrix}a \times 0 + b \times 1 \\ c \times 0 + d \times 1\end{bmatrix} \amp = \begin{bmatrix}0\\-1\end{bmatrix}</mrow>
        <mrow>\Rightarrow \begin{bmatrix}b \\ d\end{bmatrix} \amp = \begin{bmatrix}0\\-1\end{bmatrix}</mrow>
      </md>

      <p>Once again, we compare entries to get the values of <m>b</m> and <m>d</m>:</p>

      <md>
        \Rightarrow b = 0, d = -1
      </md>

      <p> Through both of these equations, we have discovered all four entries of our matrix! Thus,
        we can conclude that the <c>Z</c> gate is represented by the matrix: </p>

      <md>Z = \begin{bmatrix}1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp -1\end{bmatrix}</md>
    </example>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="gates_as_matrices_intuition" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Gates as Matrices: Intuition</title>
    <p>So far, we have explored how to express multi-qubit states in vector notation and how to
      represent 1-qubit gates in matrix form. Let's look a little closer at these gates to gain a
      little intuition
      about them.</p>

    <p> Let's start by looking at the <c>NOT</c> gate. We know that applying a <c>NOT</c> gate to a
      general qubit of the form <m>a\ket{0} + b\ket{1}</m> results in <m>b\ket{0} + a\ket{1}</m>. How does this look in vector notation?</p>

    <md>\begin{bmatrix}0 \amp 1 \\ 1 \amp 0\end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix}1 \\ 0\end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix}0 \\ 1\end{bmatrix}</md>

    <p> If we look closely at the first row of our matrix multiplication:</p>

    <md>0 \times a + 1 \times b = b</md>

    <p>we can see that this is effectively "<em>selecting</em>" the second term in our input vector
      and placing it in the first row of our output vector. We can interpret the first row of the <c>NOT</c>
      gate, <m>\begin{bmatrix}0 \amp 1\end{bmatrix}</m> as: "Pick whatever is in the second row of the input vector and set it as the
      first row of the output vector".</p>

    <p>Similarly, the second row of our matrix multiplication:</p>

    <md>1 \times a + 0 \times b</md>

    <p>is "<em>selecting</em>" the first term in our input vector and placing it in the second row
      of our output vector! Thus, the overall result of the <c>NOT</c> gate is to swap the probability
      amplitudes of the 0 (the first row) and 1 (the second row) outcomes!</p>

    <p> At this point, I encourage you to go back to our other 1-qubit gates and get a feel for
      how their matrix representations give you an intuition for how the input vector turns into
      the output vector.</p>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="multi_qubit_gates" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>2-Qubit Gates</title>

    <p>This intuition about how matrix rows "select" elements from the input row will be our guiding
      approach to deriving our 2-qubit gates, <c>SWAP</c> and <c>CNOT</c>.</p>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>Matrix representation of <c>SWAP</c></title>
      <p> Our goal here is to try to derive the <c>SWAP</c> gate by looking at how it affects a sample
        2-qubit state. This time, let's consider a general 2-qubit state, i.e. <m>a\ket{00} + b\ket{01} + c\ket{10} + d\ket{11}</m>. Using our
        knowledge of the <c>SWAP</c> gate swapping the first and second qubits in the state, we know
        that the probability amplitude of the <m>\ket{01}</m> becomes the probability amplitude of <m>\ket{10}</m>.
        Additionally, the probability amplitude of the <m>\ket{10}</m> becomes the probability amplitude of <m>\ket{01}</m>.
        The probability amplitudes of <m>\ket{00}</m> and <m>\ket{11}</m> don't change, because <c>SWAP</c> has no
        impact on these states. What does this look like in vector notation? </p>

      <md>
        \begin{bmatrix}a\\b\\c\\d\end{bmatrix} \xrightarrow{\text{SWAP}} \begin{bmatrix}a\\c\\b\\d\end{bmatrix}
      </md>

      <p> Let's now apply our intuition about how matrix rows can "select" certain values from the
        vector the matrix is multiplied with.
      </p>

      <ul>
        <li>The first row of our vector is unchanged; so the first row of the <c>SWAP</c> gate should
          have a 1 in the 1st column.</li>
        <li>The second row of our vector "<em>selects</em>" the <em>third</em> row of our input
          vector; so the second row of the gate should have a 1 in the <em>3rd</em> column.</li>
        <li>Similarly, the third row of our vector "<em>selects</em>" the <em>second</em> row of our
          input vector; so the third row of the gate should have a 1 in the <em>2nd</em> column.</li>
        <li>Finally, the fourth row of our vector is unchanged; so the fourth row has a 1 in the 4th
          column.</li>
      </ul>

      <p>Putting this together...</p>

      <md>
        \text{SWAP} = \begin{bmatrix}1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0\\0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 0\\0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0\\0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1\end{bmatrix}
      </md>

      <p>Congratulations! You just discovered the matrix representation of your first 2-qubit gate!</p>
    </paragraphs>

    <p>
      <insert>practice applying the SWAP gate on an arbitrary vector</insert>
    </p>

    <p>
      <insert>CNOT 1 to 2, walk-through exercise plus note about controlled-U view</insert>
    </p>
    <p>
      <insert>CNOT 2 to 1: just give it</insert>
    </p>
  </subsection>
</section>
